<p><a name="References" id="References"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Chinese_dragon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: References">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">References</span></h2>
<div class="references-small">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-Sleeboom-0">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Sleeboom_0-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Sleeboom_0-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Sleeboom_0-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> Sleeboom, Margaret. [2004] (2004). Academic Nations in China and Japan: Framed in Concepts of Nature, Culture and the Universe. Routledge publishing. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/041531545X" class="internal">ISBN 041531545X</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.brandhk.gov.hk/brandhk/eview.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.brandhk.gov.hk/brandhk/eview.htm" rel="nofollow">"Brand Overview"</a>, Brand Hong Kong, 09-2004. Retrieved on 23-02-2007.</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="news" id="CITEREFRobertson2004">Robertson, Benjamin (2004-12-17). "<a href="http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FL17Ad01.html" class="external text" title="http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FL17Ad01.html" rel="nofollow">The Dragon battles back to beat Nike</a>". <i><a href="/wiki/Asia_Times_Online" title="Asia Times Online">Asia Times Online</a></i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FL17Ad01.html" class="external free" title="http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FL17Ad01.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.atimes.com/atimes/China/FL17Ad01.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-03-20</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=The+Dragon+battles+back+to+beat+Nike&amp;rft.jtitle=%5B%5BAsia+Times+Online%5D%5D&amp;rft.aulast=Robertson&amp;rft.aufirst=Benjamin&amp;rft.au=Robertson%2C+Benjamin&amp;rft.date=2004-12-17&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.atimes.com%2Fatimes%2FChina%2FFL17Ad01.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Chinese_dragon"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.nga.gov/education/chinatp_sl01.htm" class="external autonumber" title="http://www.nga.gov/education/chinatp_sl01.htm" rel="nofollow">[1]</a> National Gallery of Art, Washington, DC</li>
<li id="cite_note-Visser-4">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Visser_4-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Visser_4-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> de Visser, M.W. 1913. The Dragon in China and Japan. Johannes Müller, 70.<a href="http://fax.libs.uga.edu/GR830xD7xV8/1f/dragon_in_china_and_japan.txt" class="external autonumber" title="http://fax.libs.uga.edu/GR830xD7xV8/1f/dragon_in_china_and_japan.txt" rel="nofollow">[2]</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-Dor.C3.A9-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Dor.C3.A9_5-0" title="">^</a></b> Doré, Henri. 1917. <i>Researches into Chinese Superstitions</i>. M. Kennelly, D.J. Finn, and L.F. McGreat, trs. T'usewei. Ch'eng-wen reprint 1966, 681.</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.nga.gov/exhibitions/china1999/037_010.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.nga.gov/exhibitions/china1999/037_010.htm" rel="nofollow">"Jade coiled dragon, Hongshan Culture (c. 4700-2920 B.C.)"</a>, National Gallery of Art, Washington DC. Retrieved on 23-02-2007.</li>
<li id="cite_note-Carr-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Carr_7-0" title="">^</a></b> Carr, Michael. 1990. "Chinese Dragon Names," <i>Linguistics of the Tibeto-Burman Area</i> 13.2:87-189. He classified them into seven categories: Rain-dragons, Flying-dragons, Snake-dragons, Wug-dragons [<i>wug</i> refers to "worms, bugs, and small reptiles"], Crocodile-dragons, Hill-dragons, and Miscellaneous dragons.</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> Adapted from Doré 682.</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> The <a href="/wiki/Twenty-Four_Histories" title="Twenty-Four Histories">Twenty-Four Histories</a>: The <a href="/wiki/History_of_Yuan" title="History of Yuan">History of Yuan</a>-Dress Code (<a href="http://zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%85%83%E5%8F%B2" class="extiw" title="zh:元史">zh:元史</a>·舆服), compiled under Song Lian (宋濂), 1370 AD.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<p>11. Bates, Roy, Chinese Dragons, Oxford University Press, 2002</p>
<p>12. Bates, Roy, All About Chinese Dragons, TuDragons Press, 2007</p>
